# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dynamic-equilibrium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In chemistry, an **acid–base reaction** is a chemical reaction that occurs between an acid and a base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] It can be used to determine pH via titration.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Several theoretical frameworks provide alternative conceptions of the reaction mechanisms and their application in solving related problems; these are called the acid–base theories, for example, Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Their importance becomes apparent in analyzing acid–base reactions for gaseous or liquid species, or when acid or base character may be somewhat less apparent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The first of these concepts was provided by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, around 1776.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] It is important to think of the acid–base reaction models as theories that complement each other.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] For example, the current Lewis model has the broadest definition of what an acid and base are, with the Brønsted–Lowry theory being a subset of what acids and bases are, and the Arrhenius theory being the most restrictive.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius theory describes an acid as a substance that increases the concentration of hydrogen ions (H3O+ or H+) in a solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] A base is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] However, Arrhenius's definition only applies to substances that are in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The concept of an acid–base reaction was first proposed in 1754 by Guillaume-François Rouelle, who introduced the word "base" into chemistry to mean a substance which reacts with an acid to give it solid form (as a salt).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The first scientific concept of acids and bases was provided by Lavoisier in around 1776.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Lavoisier definition held for over 30 years, until the 1810 article and subsequent lectures by Sir Humphry Davy in which he proved the lack of oxygen in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), hydrogen telluride (H2Te), and the hydrohalic acids.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] However, Davy failed to develop a new theory, concluding that "acidity does not depend upon any particular elementary substance, but upon peculiar arrangement of various substances".
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] One notable modification of oxygen theory was provided by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, who stated that acids are oxides of nonmetals while bases are oxides of metals.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In 1838, Justus von Liebig proposed that an acid is a hydrogen-containing compound whose hydrogen can be replaced by a metal.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This redefinition was based on his extensive work on the chemical composition of organic acids, finishing the doctrinal shift from oxygen-based acids to hydrogen-based acids started by Davy.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Liebig's definition, while completely empirical, remained in use for almost 50 years until the adoption of the Arrhenius definition.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The first modern definition of acids and bases in molecular terms was devised by Svante Arrhenius.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] A hydrogen theory of acids, it followed from his 1884 work with Friedrich Wilhelm Ostwald in establishing the presence of ions in aqueous solution and led to Arrhenius receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This causes the protonation of water, or the creation of the hydronium (H3O+) ion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in modern times, the symbol H+ is interpreted as a shorthand for H3O+, because it is now known that a bare proton does not exist as a free species in aqueous solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This is the species which is measured by pH indicators to measure the acidity or basicity of a solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius definitions of acidity and alkalinity are restricted to aqueous solutions and are not valid for most non-aqueous solutions, and refer to the concentration of the solvent ions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Under this definition, pure H2SO4 and HCl dissolved in toluene are not acidic, and molten NaOH and solutions of calcium amide in liquid ammonia are not alkaline.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This led to the development of the Brønsted–Lowry theory and subsequent Lewis theory to account for these non-aqueous exceptions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of an acid with a base is called a neutralization reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In this traditional representation an acid–base neutralization reaction is formulated as a double-replacement reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The modifier (aq) in this equation was implied by Arrhenius, rather than included explicitly.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] It indicates that the substances are dissolved in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Though all three substances, HCl, NaOH and NaCl are capable of existing as pure compounds, in aqueous solutions they are fully dissociated into the aquated ions H+, Cl−, Na+ and OH−.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is used to cause the dough for breads and cakes to "rise" by creating millions of tiny carbon dioxide bubbles.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is not to be confused with baking soda, which is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is a mixture of baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) and acidic salts.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The bubbles are created because, when the baking powder is combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Whether commercially or domestically prepared, the principles behind baking powder formulations remain the same.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The real reactions are more complicated because the acids are complicated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] A typical formulation (by weight) could call for 30% sodium bicarbonate, 5–12% monocalcium phosphate, and 21–26% sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Alternately, a commercial baking powder might use sodium acid pyrophosphate as one of the two acidic components instead of sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Another typical acid in such formulations is cream of tartar (KC4H5O6), a derivative of tartaric acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] An acid–base reaction is, thus, the removal of a proton from the acid and its addition to the base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The removal of a proton from an acid produces its *conjugate base*, which is the acid with a proton removed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The reception of a proton by a base produces its *conjugate acid*, which is the base with a proton added.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Unlike the previous definitions, the Brønsted–Lowry definition does not refer to the formation of salt and solvent, but instead to the formation of *conjugate acids* and *conjugate bases*, produced by the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In this approach, acids and bases are fundamentally different in behavior from salts, which are seen as electrolytes, subject to the theories of Debye, Onsager, and others.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] An acid and a base react not to produce a salt and a solvent, but to form a new acid and a new base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The concept of neutralization is thus absent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base behavior is formally independent of any solvent, making it more all-encompassing than the Arrhenius model.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The calculation of pH under the Arrhenius model depended on alkalis (bases) dissolving in water (aqueous solution).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model expanded what could be pH tested using insoluble and soluble solutions (gas, liquid, solid).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The general formula for acid–base reactions according to the Brønsted–Lowry definition is: ${\ce {HA + B -> BH+ + A-}}$ where HA represents the acid, B represents the base, BH+ represents the conjugate acid of B, and A− represents the conjugate base of HA.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The removal of H+ from the HCl produces the chloride ion, Cl−, the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The addition of H+ to the H2O (acting as a base) forms the hydronium ion, H3O+, the conjugate acid of the base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Water is amphoteric – that is, it can act as both an acid and a base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Here, one molecule of water acts as an acid, donating an H+ and forming the conjugate base, OH−, and a second molecule of water acts as a base, accepting the H+ ion and forming the conjugate acid, H3O+.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In this example, a water molecule is split into a hydrogen cation, which is donated to a pyridine molecule, and a hydroxide ion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In the Brønsted–Lowry model, the solvent does not necessarily have to be water, as is required by the Arrhenius Acid–Base model.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] An H+ ion is removed from acetic acid, forming its conjugate base, the acetate ion, CH3COO−.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The addition of an H+ ion to an ammonia molecule of the solvent creates its conjugate acid, the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model calls hydrogen-containing substances (like HCl) acids.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Thus, some substances, which many chemists considered to be acids, such as SO3 or BCl3, are excluded from this classification due to lack of hydrogen.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The hydrogen requirement of Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry was removed by the Lewis definition of acid–base reactions, devised by Gilbert N.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Lewis in 1923, in the same year as Brønsted–Lowry, but it was not elaborated by him until 1938.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Instead of defining acid–base reactions in terms of protons or other bonded substances, the Lewis definition defines a base (referred to as a *Lewis base*) to be a compound that can donate an *electron pair*, and an acid (a *Lewis acid*) to be a compound that can receive this electron pair.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] For example, boron trifluoride, BF3 is a typical Lewis acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] It can accept a pair of electrons as it has a vacancy in its octet.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The fluoride ion has a full octet and can donate a pair of electrons.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Thus ${\ce {BF3 + F- -> BF4-}}$ is a typical Lewis acid, Lewis base reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] All compounds of group 13 elements with a formula AX3 can behave as Lewis acids.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Similarly, compounds of group 15 elements with a formula DY3, such as amines, NR3, and phosphines, PR3, can behave as Lewis bases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Adducts between them have the formula X3A←DY3 with a dative covalent bond, shown symbolically as ←, between the atoms A (acceptor) and D (donor).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Compounds of group 16 with a formula DX2 may also act as Lewis bases; in this way, a compound like an ether, R2O, or a thioether, R2S, can act as a Lewis base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis definition is not limited to these examples.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] For instance, carbon monoxide acts as a Lewis base when it forms an adduct with boron trifluoride, of formula F3B←CO.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Adducts involving metal ions are referred to as co-ordination compounds; each ligand donates a pair of electrons to the metal ion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The reaction ${\ce {[Ag(H2O)4]+ + 2 NH3 -> [Ag(NH3)2]+ + 4 H2O}}$ can be seen as an acid–base reaction in which a stronger base (ammonia) replaces a weaker one (water).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are consistent with each other since the reaction ${\ce {H+ + OH- <=> H2O}}$ is an acid–base reaction in both theories.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] One of the limitations of the Arrhenius definition is its reliance on water solutions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Edward Curtis Franklin studied the acid–base reactions in liquid ammonia in 1905 and pointed out the similarities to the water-based Arrhenius theory.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Germann, working with liquid phosgene, COCl 2, formulated the solvent-based theory in 1925, thereby generalizing the Arrhenius definition to cover aprotic solvents.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvonium ions and a decrease in the concentration of solvate ions is defined as an *acid*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvate ions and a decrease in the concentration of the solvonium ions is defined as a *base*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in liquid ammonia, KNH2 (supplying NH−2) is a strong base, and NH4NO3 (supplying NH+4) is a strong acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In liquid sulfur dioxide (SO2), thionyl compounds (supplying SO2+) behave as acids, and sulfites (supplying SO2−3) behave as bases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] On the other hand, solvent system theory has been criticized as being too general to be useful.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Also, it has been thought that there is something intrinsically acidic about hydrogen compounds, a property not shared by non-hydrogenic solvonium salts.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This acid–base theory was a revival of the oxygen theory of acids and bases proposed by German chemist Hermann Lux in 1939, further improved by Håkon Flood c.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] 1947 and is still used in modern geochemistry and electrochemistry of molten salts.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This definition describes an acid as an oxide ion (O2−) acceptor and a base as an oxide ion donor.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This theory is also useful in the systematisation of the reactions of noble gas compounds, especially the xenon oxides, fluorides, and oxofluorides.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Mikhail Usanovich developed a general theory that does not restrict acidity to hydrogen-containing compounds, but his approach, published in 1938, was even more general than Lewis theory.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Usanovich's theory can be summarized as defining an acid as anything that accepts negative species or donates positive ones, and a base as the reverse.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This defined the concept of redox (oxidation-reduction) as a special case of acid–base reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In 1963, Ralph Pearson proposed a qualitative concept known as the Hard and Soft Acids and Bases principle. later made quantitative with help of Robert Parr in 1984.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] 'Hard' applies to species that are small, have high charge states, and are weakly polarizable.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] 'Soft' applies to species that are large, have low charge states and are strongly polarizable.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Acids and bases interact, and the most stable interactions are hard–hard and soft–soft.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] This theory has found use in organic and inorganic chemistry.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Drago is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The model assigned E and C parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Each acid is characterized by an *E*A and a *C*A.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Each base is likewise characterized by its own *E*B and *C*B.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The E and C parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The W term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The equation predicts reversal of acids and base strengths.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of a strong acid with a strong base is essentially a quantitative reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] In this reaction both the sodium and chloride ions are spectators as the neutralization reaction, ${\ce {H+ + OH- -> H2O}}$ does not involve them.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] With weak bases addition of acid is not quantitative because a solution of a weak base is a buffer solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] A solution of a weak acid is also a buffer solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] When a weak acid reacts with a weak base an equilibrium mixture is produced.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] The notation [X] signifies "concentration of X".
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] An acid–alkali reaction is a special case of an acid–base reaction, where the base used is also an alkali.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] When an acid reacts with an alkali salt (a metal hydroxide), the product is a metal salt and water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Acid–alkali reactions are also neutralization reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Acids are in general pure substances that contain hydrogen cations (H+) or cause them to be produced in solutions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-base-reaction] Hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4) are common examples.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] The **binding constant**, or **affinity constant/association constant**, is a special case of the equilibrium constant *K*, and is the inverse of the dissociation constant.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] It is associated with the binding and unbinding reaction of molecules.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] The reaction is characterized by the on-rate constant *k*on and the off-rate constant *k*off, which have units of M−1 s−1 and s−1, respectively.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] In equilibrium, the forward binding transition X + Y → XY should be balanced by the backward unbinding transition XY → X + Y.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] where [X] and [Y] represent the concentration of unbound molecules, while [XY] represents the concentration of bound complexes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] An often considered quantity is the dissociation constant *K*d ≡ ⁠1/*K*a⁠, which has the unit of concentration, despite the fact that strictly speaking, all association constants are unitless values.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] The inclusion of units arises from the simplification that such constants are calculated solely from concentrations, which is not the case.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] Once chemical activity is factored into the correct form of the equation, a dimensionless value is obtained.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-constant] in which *R* is the ideal gas constant, *T* temperature and the standard reference concentration *c*o = 1 mol/L.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In chemistry, **binding selectivity** is defined with respect to the binding of ligands to a substrate forming a complex.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Binding selectivity describes how a ligand may bind more preferentially to one receptor than another.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] A selectivity coefficient is the equilibrium constant for the reaction of displacement by one ligand of another ligand in a complex with the substrate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Binding selectivity is of major importance in biochemistry and in chemical separation processes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The concept of selectivity is used to quantify the extent to which one chemical substance, A, binds each of two other chemical substances, B and C.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The simplest case is where the complexes formed have 1:1 stoichiometry.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] It is easy to show that the same definition applies to complexes of a different stoichiometry, A*p*B*q* and A*p*C*q*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The greater the selectivity coefficient, the more the ligand C will displace the ligand B from the complex formed with the substrate A.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] An alternative interpretation is that the greater the selectivity coefficient, the lower the concentration of C that is needed to displace B from AB.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Selectivity coefficients are determined experimentally by measuring the two equilibrium constants, *K*AB and *K*AC.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In biochemistry the substrate is known as a receptor.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] A receptor is a protein molecule, embedded in either the plasma membrane or the cytoplasm of a cell, to which one or more specific kinds of signalling molecules may bind.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] A ligand may be a peptide or another small molecule, such as a neurotransmitter, a hormone, a pharmaceutical drug, or a toxin.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The specificity of a receptor is determined by its spatial geometry and the way it binds to the ligand through non-covalent interactions, such as hydrogen bonding or Van der Waals forces.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] If a receptor can be isolated a synthetic drug can be developed either to stimulate the receptor, an agonist or to block it, an antagonist.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The stomach ulcer drug cimetidine was developed as an H2 antagonist by chemically engineering the molecule for maximum specificity to an isolated tissue containing the receptor.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The further use of quantitative structure-activity relationships (QSAR) led to the development of other agents such as ranitidine.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] "Selectivity" when referring to a drug is relative.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] For example, in a higher dose, a specific drug molecule may also bind to other receptors than those said to be "selective".
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Chelation therapy is a form of medical treatment in which a chelating ligand is used to selectively remove a metal from the body.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] When the metal exists as a divalent ion, such as with lead, Pb2+ or mercury, Hg2+ selectivity against calcium, Ca2+ and magnesium, Mg2+, is essential in order that the treatment does not remove essential metals.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Selectivity is determined by various factors.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In the case of iron overload, which may occur in individuals with β-thalessemia who have received blood transfusions, the target metal ion is in the +3 oxidation state and so forms stronger complexes than the divalent ions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] It also forms stronger complexes with oxygen-donor ligands than with nitrogen-donor ligands. deferoxamine, a naturally occurring siderophore produced by the actinobacter *Streptomyces pilosus* and was used initially as a chelation therapy agent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Synthetic siderophores such as deferiprone and deferasirox have been developed, using the known structure of deferoxamine as a starting point.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Chelation occurs with the two oxygen atoms.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Wilson's disease is caused by a defect in copper metabolism which results in accumulation of copper metal in various organs of the body.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The target ion in this case is divalent, Cu2+.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] This ion is classified as borderline in the scheme of Ahrland, Chatt and Davies.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] This means that it forms roughly equally strong complexes with ligands whose donor atoms are N, O or F as with ligands whose donor atoms are P, S or Cl.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Penicillamine, which contains nitrogen and sulphur donor atoms, is used as this type of ligand binds more strongly to copper ions than to calcium and magnesium ions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Treatment of poisoning by heavy metals such as lead and mercury is more problematical, because the ligands used do not have high specificity relative to calcium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] For example, EDTA may be administered as a calcium salt to reduce the removal of calcium from bone together with the heavy metal.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Factors determining selectivity for lead against zinc, cadmium and calcium have been reviewed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In column chromatography a mixture of substances is dissolved in a mobile phase and passed over a stationary phase in a column.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] A selectivity factor is defined as the ratio of distribution coefficients, which describe the equilibrium distribution of an analyte between the stationary phase and the mobile phase.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The selectivity factor is equal to the selectivity coefficient with the added assumption that the activity of the stationary phase, the substrate in this case, is equal to 1, the standard assumption for a pure phase.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] where α is selectivity factor, *N* is the number of theoretical plates *k*A and *k*B are the retention factors of the two analytes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Retention factors are proportional to distribution coefficients.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In practice substances with a selectivity factor very close to 1 can be separated.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] This is particularly true in gas-liquid chromatography where column lengths up to 60 m are possible, providing a very large number of theoretical plates.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Solvent extraction is used to extract individual lanthanoid elements from the mixtures found in nature in ores such as monazite.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In one process, the metal ions in aqueous solution are made to form complexes with tributylphosphate (TBP), which are extracted into an organic solvent such as kerosene.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Complete separation is effected by using a countercurrent exchange method.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] A number of cells are arranged as a cascade.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] After equilibration, the aqueous component of each cell is transferred to the previous cell and the organic component is transferred to the next cell, which initially contains only water.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In this way the metal ion with the most stable complex passes down the cascade in the organic phase and the metal with the least stable complex passes up the cascade in the aqueous phase.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] If solubility in the organic phase is not an issue, a selectivity coefficient is equal to the ratio of the stability constants of the TBP complexes of two metal ions.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] For lanthanoid elements which are adjacent in the periodic table this ratio is not much greater than 1, so many cells are needed in the cascade.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] A potentiometric selectivity coefficient defines the ability of an ion-selective electrode to distinguish one particular ion from others.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The selectivity coefficient, KB,C is evaluated by means of the emf response of the ion-selective electrode in mixed solutions of the primary ion, B, and interfering ion, C (fixed interference method) or less desirably, in separate solutions of B and C (separate solution method).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] For example, a potassium ion-selective membrane electrode utilizes the naturally occurring macrocyclic antibiotic valinomycin.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] In this case the cavity in the macrocyclic ring is just the right size to encapsulate the potassium ion, but too large to bind the sodium ion, the most likely interference, strongly.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] Chemical sensors, are being developed for specific target molecules and ions in which the target (guest) form a complex with a sensor (host).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The sensor is designed to be an excellent match in terms of the size and shape of the target in order to provide for the maximum binding selectivity.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] An indicator is associated with the sensor which undergoes a change when the target forms a complex with the sensor .
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The indicator change is usually a colour change (gray to yellow in the illustration) seen in absorbance or, with greater sensitivity, luminescence.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/binding-selectivity] The indicator may be attached to the sensor via a spacer, in the ISR arrangement, or it may be displaced from the sensor, IDA arrangement.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] A **buffer solution** is a solution where the pH does not change significantly on dilution or if an acid or base is added at constant temperature.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Its pH changes very little when a small amount of strong acid or base is added to it.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Buffer solutions are used as a means of keeping pH at a nearly constant value in a wide variety of chemical applications.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] In nature, there are many living systems that use buffering for pH regulation.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] For example, the bicarbonate buffering system is used to regulate the pH of blood, and bicarbonate also acts as a buffer in the ocean.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] When some strong acid is added to an equilibrium mixture of the weak acid and its conjugate base, hydrogen ions (H+) are added, and the equilibrium is shifted to the left, in accordance with Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Because of this, the hydrogen ion concentration increases by less than the amount expected for the quantity of strong acid added.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Similarly, if strong alkali is added to the mixture, the hydrogen ion concentration decreases by less than the amount expected for the quantity of alkali added.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] In Figure 1, the effect is illustrated by the simulated titration of a weak acid with p*K*a = 4.7.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The relative concentration of undissociated acid is shown in blue, and of its conjugate base in red.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The pH changes relatively slowly in the buffer region, pH = p*K*a ± 1, centered at pH = 4.7, where [HA] = [A−].
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Once the acid is more than 95% deprotonated, the pH rises rapidly because most of the added alkali is consumed in the neutralization reaction.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Buffer capacity is a quantitative measure of the resistance to change of pH of a solution containing a buffering agent with respect to a change of acid or alkali concentration.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] *K*w is the equilibrium constant for self-ionization of water, equal to 1.0×10−14.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Note that in solution H+ exists as the hydronium ion H3O+, and further aquation of the hydronium ion has negligible effect on the dissociation equilibrium, except at very high acid concentration.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] This equation shows that there are three regions of raised buffer capacity (see figure 2).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The pH of a solution containing a buffering agent can only vary within a narrow range, regardless of what else may be present in the solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] In biological systems this is an essential condition for enzymes to function correctly.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] For example, in human blood a mixture of carbonic acid (H 2CO 3) and bicarbonate (HCO− 3) is present in the plasma fraction; this constitutes the major mechanism for maintaining the pH of blood between 7.35 and 7.45.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Outside this narrow range (7.40 ± 0.05 pH unit), acidosis and alkalosis metabolic conditions rapidly develop, ultimately leading to death if the correct buffering capacity is not rapidly restored.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] If the pH value of a solution rises or falls too much, the effectiveness of an enzyme decreases in a process, known as denaturation, which is usually irreversible.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The majority of biological samples that are used in research are kept in a buffer solution, often phosphate buffered saline (PBS) at pH 7.4.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] In industry, buffering agents are used in fermentation processes and in setting the correct conditions for dyes used in colouring fabrics.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] They are also used in chemical analysis and calibration of pH meters.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] For buffers in acid regions, the pH may be adjusted to a desired value by adding a strong acid such as hydrochloric acid to the particular buffering agent.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] For alkaline buffers, a strong base such as sodium hydroxide may be added.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Alternatively, a buffer mixture can be made from a mixture of an acid and its conjugate base.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] For example, an acetate buffer can be made from a mixture of acetic acid and sodium acetate.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Similarly, an alkaline buffer can be made from a mixture of the base and its conjugate acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] By combining substances with p*K*a values differing by only two or less and adjusting the pH, a wide range of buffers can be obtained.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Citric acid is a useful component of a buffer mixture because it has three p*K*a values, separated by less than two.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The buffer range can be extended by adding other buffering agents.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The following mixtures (McIlvaine's buffer solutions) have a buffer range of pH 3 to 8.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] A mixture containing citric acid, monopotassium phosphate, boric acid, and diethyl barbituric acid can be made to cover the pH range 2.6 to 12.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Other universal buffers are the Carmody buffer and the Britton–Robinson buffer, developed in 1931.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] For effective range see Buffer capacity, above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Also see Good's buffers for the historic design principles and favourable properties of these buffer substances in biochemical applications.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] This shows that when the acid dissociates, equal amounts of hydrogen ion and anion are produced.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The equilibrium concentrations of these three components can be calculated in an ICE table (ICE standing for "initial, change, equilibrium").
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The first row, labelled **I**, lists the initial conditions: the concentration of acid is *C*0, initially undissociated, so the concentrations of A− and H+ would be zero; *y* is the initial concentration of *added* strong acid, such as hydrochloric acid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] If strong alkali, such as sodium hydroxide, is added, then *y* will have a negative sign because alkali removes hydrogen ions from the solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The second row, labelled **C** for "change", specifies the changes that occur when the acid dissociates.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The acid concentration decreases by an amount −*x*, and the concentrations of A− and H+ both increase by an amount +*x*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] This follows from the equilibrium expression.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The third row, labelled **E** for "equilibrium", adds together the first two rows and shows the concentrations at equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] With specific values for *C*0, *K*a and *y*, this equation can be solved for *x*.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Assuming that pH = −log10[H+], the pH can be calculated as pH = −log10(*x* + *y*).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Polyprotic acids are acids that can lose more than one proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1, and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Citric acid is an example of a polyprotic acid H3A, as it can lose three protons.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] When the difference between successive p*K*a values is less than about 3, there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] In the case of citric acid, the overlap is extensive and solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Calculation of the pH with a polyprotic acid requires a speciation calculation to be performed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] The numbering of cumulative, overall constants is the reverse of the numbering of the stepwise, dissociation constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/buffer-solution] Cumulative association constants are used in general-purpose computer programs such as the one used to obtain the speciation diagram above.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In chemistry, a **dynamic equilibrium** exists once a reversible reaction occurs.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Substances initially transition between the reactants and products at different rates until the forward and backward reaction rates eventually equalize, meaning there is no net change.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Reactants and products are formed at such a rate that the concentration of neither changes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] It is a particular example of a system in a steady state.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In a new bottle of soda, the concentration of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the liquid phase has a particular value.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] If half of the liquid is poured out and the bottle is sealed, carbon dioxide will leave the liquid phase at an ever-decreasing rate, and the partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the gas phase will increase until equilibrium is reached.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] At that point, due to thermal motion, a molecule of CO2 may leave the liquid phase, but within a very short time another molecule of CO2 will pass from the gas to the liquid, and vice versa.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] At equilibrium, the rate of transfer of CO2 from the gas to the liquid phase is equal to the rate from liquid to gas.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In this case, the equilibrium concentration of CO2 in the liquid is given by Henry's law, which states that the solubility of a gas in a liquid is directly proportional to the partial pressure of that gas above the liquid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] where *K* is a temperature-dependent constant, *P* is the partial pressure, and *c* is the concentration of the dissolved gas in the liquid.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Thus the partial pressure of CO2 in the gas has increased until Henry's law is obeyed.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] The concentration of carbon dioxide in the liquid has decreased and the drink has lost some of its fizz.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Henry's law may be derived by setting the chemical potentials of carbon dioxide in the two phases to be equal to each other.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Equality of chemical potential defines chemical equilibrium.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Other constants for dynamic equilibrium involving phase changes include partition coefficient and solubility product.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Raoult's law defines the equilibrium vapor pressure of an ideal solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Dynamic equilibrium can also exist in a single-phase system.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] A simple example occurs with acid–base equilibrium such as the dissociation of acetic acid in an aqueous solution.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In this case, the forward reaction involves the liberation of some protons from acetic acid molecules and the backward reaction involves the formation of acetic acid molecules when an acetate ion accepts a proton.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Equilibrium is attained when the sum of chemical potentials of the species on the left-hand side of the equilibrium expression is equal to the sum of chemical potentials of the species on the right-hand side.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] At the same time, the rates of forward and backward reactions are equal to each other.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Equilibria involving the formation of chemical complexes are also dynamic equilibria and concentrations are governed by the stability constants of complexes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Dynamic equilibria can also occur in the gas phase; for example, when nitrogen dioxide dimerizes.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In the gas phase, square brackets indicate partial pressure.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] Alternatively, the partial pressure of a substance may be written as P(substance).
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] There are two reactions to consider, the forward reaction in which the species A is converted into B and the reverse reaction in which B is converted into A.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] where kf is the rate constant for the forward reaction and kb is the rate constant for the backward reaction and the square brackets, [...], denote concentration.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] If only A is present at the beginning, time *t* = 0, with a concentration [A]0, the sum of the two concentrations, [A]*t* and [B]*t*, at time t, will be equal to [A]0.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] As time tends towards infinity, the concentrations [A]*t* and [B]*t* tend towards constant values.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In practice, concentration changes will not be measurable after ${\textstyle t\gtrapprox {\frac {10}{k_{f}+k_{b}}}.}$ Since the concentrations do not change thereafter, they are, by definition, equilibrium concentrations.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] It follows that the equilibrium constant is numerically equal to the quotient of the rate constants.
[src:dynamic-equilibrium/dynamic-equilibrium] In general, there may be more than one forward reaction and more than one backward reaction.
